Find the equation of the oblique asympto:
To find the equation of the oblique asymptote, we divide the numerator $4x^2 - 10x + 7$ by the denominator $2x - 5$ using long division:

\[
\begin{array}{c|cc cc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{2x} & +3 \\
\cline{2-5}
2x - 5 & 4x^2 & -10x & +0x & + 7 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{4x^2} & -10x \\
\cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 0x & + 7 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & \multicolumn{2}{r}{-7} \\
\cline{4-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & 0 \\
\end{array}
\]So, we have that
\[y = \frac{4x^2 - 10x + 7}{2x - 5} = 2x + 3 + \frac{-7}{2x - 5}.\]As $x$ gets large, the term $\tfrac{-7}{2x - 5}$ approaches 0, so the oblique asymptote is $\boxed{y = 2x + 3}.$

